From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date: Thu, 2 Jul 2026 08:54:32 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] kati: propagate MAKEFLAGS to in-process sub-makes through the
 recipe env
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The Linux kernel build failed at parse in a -b box:

    linux/Makefile:334: scripts/Kbuild.include: No such file or directory

The kernel's top Makefile detects srctree != objtree, appends
`MAKEFLAGS += --include-dir=$(abs_srctree)`, exports sub_make_done=1
and re-invokes itself; the second pass relies on the ENVIRONMENT
MAKEFLAGS carrying --include-dir so its bare `include
scripts/Kbuild.include` resolves from the source tree. In a box every
$(MAKE) is an in-process builtin sharing ONE process env, so the
appended flags died at the process-env boundary: run_kati skipped
MAKEFLAGS in the export prefix, and Flags::from_args read MAKEFLAGS
only from std::env — never from the sub-make's seed_env.

- run_kati composes $(MAKEFLAGS) from the make's OWN inherited env
  (seed_env) first, grafting in any live process-env tokens (the
  jobserver advertisement) and this invocation's long-form flags,
  deduped by word.

- run_kati emits the FINAL evaluated $(MAKEFLAGS) into the recipe
  export prefix — GNU make always passes MAKEFLAGS to children through
  the environment, including makefile-level appends.

- flags.rs: the MAKEFLAGS token parse is extracted to
  Flags::apply_makeflags (idempotent — include_dirs/cl_vars dedupe);
  make_builtin folds in the seed_env MAKEFLAGS after from_args so an
  inherited --include-dir/-rR actually reaches the evaluator.

test_make_rs case 20 replicates the v5.6 sub-make dance end-to-end in
a box; it fails with the exact user-visible error pre-fix.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
